[src:lex-yacc/compiler-compiler] "A metacompiler assists the task of compiler-building by automating its non creative aspects, those aspects that are the same regardless of the language which the produced compiler is to translate.
[src:lex-yacc/compiler-compiler] This makes possible the design of languages which are appropriate to the specification of a particular problem.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] *Deterministic* refers to the uniqueness of the computation run.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] In search of the simplest models to capture finite-state machines, Warren McCulloch and Walter Pitts were among the first researchers to introduce a concept similar to finite automata in 1943.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The figure illustrates a deterministic finite automaton using a state diagram.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] In this example automaton, there are three states: S0, S1, and S2 (denoted graphically by circles).
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The automaton takes a finite sequence of 0s and 1s as input.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each state, there is a transition arrow leading out to a next state for both 0 and 1.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Upon reading a symbol, a DFA jumps *deterministically* from one state to another by following the transition arrow.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, if the automaton is currently in state S0 and the current input symbol is 1, then it deterministically jumps to state S1.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA has a *start state* (denoted graphically by an arrow coming in from nowhere) where computations begin, and a set of *accept states* (denoted graphically by a double circle) which help define when a computation is successful.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is defined as an abstract mathematical concept, but is often implemented in hardware and software for solving various specific problems such as lexical analysis and pattern matching.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For example, a DFA can model software that decides whether or not online user input such as email addresses are syntactically valid.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs have been generalized to *nondeterministic finite automata (NFA)* which may have several arrows of the same label starting from a state.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Using the powerset construction method, every NFA can be translated to a DFA that recognizes the same language.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs, and NFAs as well, recognize exactly the set of regular languages.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Let *w* = *a*1*a*2...*an* be a string over the alphabet Σ.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] In words, the first condition says that the machine starts in the start state *q*0.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The second condition says that given each character of string w, the machine will transition from state to state according to the transition function δ.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The last condition says that the machine accepts w if the last input of w causes the machine to halt in one of the accepting states.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Otherwise, it is said that the automaton *rejects* the string.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The set of strings that M accepts is the language *recognized* by M and this language is denoted by *L*(*M*).
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A deterministic finite automaton without accept states and without a starting state is known as a transition system or semiautomaton.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For more comprehensive introduction of the formal definition see automata theory.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The following example is of a DFA M, with a binary alphabet, which requires that the input contains an even number of 0s.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The state *S*1 represents that there has been an even number of 0s in the input so far, while *S*2 signifies an odd number.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A 1 in the input does not change the state of the automaton.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the input ends, the state will show whether the input contained an even number of 0s or not.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] If the input did contain an even number of 0s, M will finish in state *S*1, an accepting state, so the input string will be accepted.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language recognized by M is the regular language given by the regular expression `(1*) (0 (1*) 0 (1*))*`, where `*` is the Kleene star, e.g., `1*` denotes any number (possibly zero) of consecutive ones.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] According to the above definition, deterministic finite automata are always *complete*: they define from each state a transition for each input symbol.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] While this is the most common definition, some authors use the term deterministic finite automaton for a slightly different notion: an automaton that defines *at most* one transition for each state and each input symbol; the transition function is allowed to be partial.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] When no transition is defined, such an automaton halts.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **local automaton** is a DFA, not necessarily complete, for which all edges with the same label lead to a single vertex.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Local automata accept the class of local languages, those for which membership of a word in the language is determined by a "sliding window" of length two on the word.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A **Myhill graph** over an alphabet *A* is a directed graph with vertex set *A* and subsets of vertices labelled "start" and "finish".
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The language accepted by a Myhill graph is the set of directed paths from a start vertex to a finish vertex: the graph thus acts as an automaton.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The class of languages accepted by Myhill graphs is the class of local languages.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] When the start state and accept states are ignored, a DFA of n states and an alphabet of size k can be seen as a digraph of n vertices in which all vertices have k out-arcs labeled 1, ..., *k* (a k-out digraph).
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] It is known that when *k* ≥ 2 is a fixed integer, with high probability, the largest strongly connected component (SCC) in such a k-out digraph chosen uniformly at random is of linear size and it can be reached by all vertices.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] It has also been proven that if k is allowed to increase as n increases, then the whole digraph has a phase transition for strong connectivity similar to Erdős–Rényi model for connectivity.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] In a random DFA, the maximum number of vertices reachable from one vertex is very close to the number of vertices in the largest SCC with high probability.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is also true for the largest induced sub-digraph of minimum in-degree one, which can be seen as a directed version of 1-core.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] If DFAs recognize the languages that are obtained by applying an operation on the DFA recognizable languages then DFAs are said to be closed under the operation.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The DFAs are closed under the following operations.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For each operation, an optimal construction with respect to the number of states has been determined in state complexity research.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Since DFAs are equivalent to nondeterministic finite automata (NFA), these closures may also be proved using closure properties of NFA.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of a given DFA can be seen as a sequence of compositions of a very general formulation of the transition function with itself.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For a given input symbol $a\in \Sigma$ , one may construct a transition function $\delta _{a}:Q\rightarrow Q$ by defining $\delta _{a}(q)=\delta (q,a)$ for all $q\in Q$ .
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] (This trick is called currying.) From this perspective, $\delta _{a}$ "acts" on a state in Q to yield another state.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] One may then consider the result of function composition repeatedly applied to the various functions $\delta _{a}$ , $\delta _{b}$ , and so on.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a pair of letters $a,b\in \Sigma$ , one may define a new function ${\widehat {\delta }}_{ab}=\delta _{a}\circ \delta _{b}$ , where $\circ$ denotes function composition.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] ${\widehat {\delta }}$ is defined for all words $w\in \Sigma ^{*}$ .
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A run of the DFA is a sequence of compositions of ${\widehat {\delta }}$ with itself.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Repeated function composition forms a monoid.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] For the transition functions, this monoid is known as the transition monoid, or sometimes the *transformation semigroup*.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The construction can also be reversed: given a ${\widehat {\delta }}$ , one can reconstruct a $\delta$ , and so the two descriptions are equivalent.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are one of the most practical models of computation, since there is a trivial linear time, constant-space, online algorithm to simulate a DFA on a stream of input.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] DFAs are equivalent in computing power to nondeterministic finite automata (NFAs).
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] This is because, firstly any DFA is also an NFA, so an NFA can do what a DFA can do.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Also, given an NFA, using the powerset construction one can build a DFA that recognizes the same language as the NFA, although the DFA could have exponentially larger number of states than the NFA.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, even though NFAs are computationally equivalent to DFAs, the above-mentioned problems are not necessarily solved efficiently also for NFAs.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The non-universality problem for NFAs is PSPACE complete since there are small NFAs with shortest rejecting word in exponential size.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] A DFA is universal if and only if all states are final states, but this does not hold for NFAs.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The Equality, Inclusion and Minimization Problems are also PSPACE complete since they require forming the complement of an NFA which results in an exponential blow up of size.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] On the other hand, finite-state automata are of strictly limited power in the languages they can recognize; many simple languages, including any problem that requires more than constant space to solve, cannot be recognized by a DFA.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The classic example of a simply described language that no DFA can recognize is bracket or Dyck language, i.e., the language that consists of properly paired brackets such as word "(()())".
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Intuitively, no DFA can recognize the Dyck language because DFAs are not capable of counting: a DFA-like automaton needs to have a state to represent any possible number of "currently open" parentheses, meaning it would need an unbounded number of states.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another simpler example is the language consisting of strings of the form *anbn* for some finite but arbitrary number of *a*'s, followed by an equal number of *b*'s.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Given a set of *positive* words $S^{+}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ and a set of *negative* words $S^{-}\subset \Sigma ^{*}$ one can construct a DFA that accepts all words from $S^{+}$ and rejects all words from $S^{-}$ : this problem is called *DFA identification* (synthesis, learning).
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] While *some* DFA can be constructed in linear time, the problem of identifying a DFA with the minimal number of states is NP-complete.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The first algorithm for minimal DFA identification has been proposed by Trakhtenbrot and Barzdin and is called the *TB-algorithm*.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, the TB-algorithm assumes that all words from $\Sigma$ up to a given length are contained in either $S^{+}\cup S^{-}$ .
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Lang proposed an extension of the TB-algorithm that does not use any assumptions about $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ , the *Traxbar* algorithm.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] However, Traxbar does not guarantee the minimality of the constructed DFA.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold also proposed a heuristic algorithm for minimal DFA identification.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Gold's algorithm assumes that $S^{+}$ and $S^{-}$ contain a *characteristic set* of the regular language; otherwise, the constructed DFA will be inconsistent either with $S^{+}$ or $S^{-}$ .
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Other notable DFA identification algorithms include the RPNI algorithm, the Blue-Fringe evidence-driven state-merging algorithm, and Windowed-EDSM.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Yet another step forward is due to application of SAT solvers by Marjin J.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Verwer: the minimal DFA identification problem is reduced to deciding the satisfiability of a Boolean formula.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Though this approach allows finding the minimal DFA, it suffers from exponential blow-up of execution time when the size of input data increases.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Therefore, Heule and Verwer's initial algorithm has later been augmented with making several steps of the EDSM algorithm prior to SAT solver execution: the DFASAT algorithm.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] This allows reducing the search space of the problem, but leads to loss of the minimality guarantee.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] Another way of reducing the search space has been proposed by Ulyantsev et al. by means of new symmetry breaking predicates based on the breadth-first search algorithm: the sought DFA's states are constrained to be numbered according to the BFS algorithm launched from the initial state.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] This approach reduces the search space by $C!$ by eliminating isomorphic automata.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] The machine always accepts a regular language.
[src:lex-yacc/deterministic-finite-automaton] There must exist at least one element of the set F (a **HALT** state) for the language to be nonempty.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The generated parsers are portable: they do not require any specific compilers.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison by default generates LALR(1) parsers but it can also generate canonical LR, IELR(1) and GLR parsers.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Flex, an automatic lexical analyser, is often used with Bison, to tokenise input data and provide Bison with tokens.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison was originally written by Robert Corbett in 1985.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Later, in 1989, Robert Corbett released another parser generator named Berkeley Yacc.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison was made Yacc-compatible by Richard Stallman.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison is free software and is available under the GNU General Public License, with an exception (discussed below) allowing its generated code to be used without triggering the copyleft requirements of the licence.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] One delicate issue with LR parser generators is the resolution of conflicts (shift/reduce and reduce/reduce conflicts).
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] With many LR parser generators, resolving conflicts requires the analysis of the parser automaton, which demands some expertise from the user.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] To aid the user in understanding conflicts more intuitively, Bison can instead automatically generate counterexamples.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] For ambiguous grammars, Bison often can even produce counterexamples that show the grammar is ambiguous.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Reentrancy is a feature which has been added to Bison and does not exist in Yacc.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Normally, Bison generates a parser which is not reentrant.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] In order to achieve reentrancy the declaration `%define api.pure` must be used.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] More details on Bison reentrancy can be found in the Bison manual.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison can generate code for C, C++, D and Java.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] For using the Bison-generated parser from other languages a language binding tool such as SWIG can be used.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Because Bison generates source code that in turn gets added to the source code of other software projects, it raises some simple but interesting copyright questions.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The code generated by Bison includes significant amounts of code from the Bison project itself.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The Bison package is distributed under the terms of the GNU General Public License (GPL) but an exception has been added so that the GPL does not apply to output.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Earlier releases of Bison stipulated that parts of its output were also licensed under the GPL, due to the inclusion of the yyparse() function from the original source code in the output.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Free software projects that use Bison may have a choice of whether to distribute the source code which their project feeds into Bison, or the resulting C code made output by Bison.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Both are sufficient for a recipient to be able to compile the project source code.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] However, distributing only the input carries the minor inconvenience that the recipients must have a compatible copy of Bison installed so that they can generate the necessary C code when compiling the project.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] And distributing only the C code in output, creates the problem of making it very difficult for the recipients to modify the parser since this code was written neither *by* a human nor *for* humans - its purpose is to be fed directly into a C compiler.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] These problems can be avoided by distributing both the input files and the generated code.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Most people will compile using the generated code, no different from any other software package, but anyone who wants to modify the parser component can modify the input files first and re-generate the generated files before compiling.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Projects distributing both usually do not have the generated files in their version control systems.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The files are only generated when making a release.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Some licenses, such as the GPL, require that the source code be in "*the preferred form of the work for making modifications to it*".
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] GPL'd projects using Bison must thus distribute the files which are the input for Bison.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Of course, they can also include the generated files.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Because Bison was written as a replacement for Yacc, and is largely compatible, the code from a lot of projects using Bison could equally be fed into Yacc.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] This makes it difficult to determine if a project "uses" Bison-specific source code or not.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] In many cases, the "use" of Bison could trivially be replaced by the equivalent use of Yacc or one of its other derivatives.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Bison has features not found in Yacc, so some projects can truly be said to "use" Bison, since Yacc would not suffice.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The following list is of projects which are known to "use" Bison in the looser sense, that they use free software development tools and distribute code which is intended to be fed into Bison or a Bison-compatible package.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The following example shows how to use Bison and flex to write a simple calculator program (only addition and multiplication) and a program for creating an abstract syntax tree.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The next two files provide definition and implementation of the syntax tree functions.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The tokens needed by the Bison parser will be generated using flex.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The names of the tokens are typically neutral: "TOKEN_PLUS" and "TOKEN_STAR", not "TOKEN_ADD" and "TOKEN_MULTIPLY".
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] For instance if we were to support the unary "+" (as in "+1"), it would be wrong to name this "+" "TOKEN_ADD".
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] In a language such as C, "int *ptr" denotes the definition of a pointer, not a product: it would be wrong to name this "*" "TOKEN_MULTIPLY".
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Since the tokens are provided by flex we must provide the means to communicate between the parser and the lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The data type used for communication, *YYSTYPE*, is set using Bison *%union* declaration.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] Since in this sample we use the reentrant version of both flex and yacc we are forced to provide parameters for the *yylex* function, when called from *yyparse*.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] This is done through Bison *%lex-param* and *%parse-param* declarations.
[src:lex-yacc/gnu-bison] The code needed to obtain the syntax tree using the parser generated by Bison and the scanner generated by flex is the following.
