[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Lex reads an input stream specifying the lexical analyzer and writes source code which implements the lexical analyzer in the C programming language.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] In addition to C, some old versions of Lex could generate a lexer in Ratfor.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Lex was originally written by Mike Lesk and Eric Schmidt and described in 1975.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] In the following years, Lex became the standard lexical analyzer generator on many Unix and Unix-like systems.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] In 1983, Lex was one of several UNIX tools available for Charles River Data Systems' UNOS operating system under the Bell Laboratories license.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Although originally distributed as proprietary software, some versions of Lex are now open-source.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Open-source versions of Lex, based on the original proprietary code, are now distributed with open-source operating systems such as OpenSolaris and Plan 9 from Bell Labs.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] One popular open-source version of Lex, called flex, or the "fast lexical analyzer", is not derived from proprietary coding.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] The following is an example Lex file for the flex version of Lex.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] It recognizes strings of numbers (positive integers) in the input, and simply prints them out.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] If this input is given to `flex`, it will be converted into a C file, `lex.yy.c`.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] This can be compiled into an executable which matches and outputs strings of integers.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Lex, as with other lexical analyzers, limits rules to those which can be described by regular expressions.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Due to this, Lex can be implemented by a finite-state automata as shown by the Chomsky hierarchy of languages.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] To recognize more complex languages, Lex is often used with parser generators such as Yacc or Bison.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Parser generators use a formal grammar to parse an input stream.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] It is typically preferable to have a parser, one generated by Yacc for instance, accept a stream of tokens (a "token-stream") as input, rather than having to process a stream of characters (a "character-stream") directly.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Lex is often used to produce such a token-stream.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Scannerless parsing refers to parsing the input character-stream directly, without a distinct lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] make is a utility that can be used to maintain programs involving Lex.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] Make assumes that a file that has an extension of `.l` is a Lex source file.
[src:lex-yacc/lex-software] The make internal macro `LFLAGS` can be used to specify Lex options to be invoked automatically by make.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A rule-based program, performing lexical tokenization, is called *tokenizer*, or *scanner*, although *scanner* is also a term for the first stage of a lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A lexer forms the first phase of a compiler frontend in processing.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexers and parsers are most often used for compilers, but can be used for other computer language tools, such as prettyprinters or linters.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexing can be divided into two stages: the *scanning*, which segments the input string into syntactic units called *lexemes* and categorizes these into token classes, and the *evaluating*, which converts lexemes into processed values.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexers are generally quite simple, with most of the complexity deferred to the syntactic analysis or semantic analysis phases, and can often be generated by a lexer generator, notably lex or derivatives.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] However, lexers can sometimes include some complexity, such as phrase structure processing to make input easier and simplify the parser, and may be written partly or fully by hand, either to support more features or for performance.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing is not equal to what is called lexeme in linguistics.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] What is called "lexeme" in rule-based natural language processing can be equal to the linguistic equivalent only in analytic languages, such as English, but not in highly synthetic languages, such as fusional languages.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] What is called a lexeme in rule-based natural language processing is more similar to what is called a word in linguistics (not to be confused with a word in computer architecture), although in some cases it may be more similar to a morpheme.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A *lexical token* is a string with an assigned and thus identified meaning, in contrast to the probabilistic token used in large language models.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A lexical token consists of a *token name* and an optional *token value*.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The token name is a category of a rule-based lexical unit.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A token name is what might be termed a part of speech in linguistics.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] the string is not implicitly segmented on spaces, as a natural language speaker would do.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The raw input, the 43 characters, must be explicitly split into the 9 tokens with a given space delimiter (i.e., matching the string `" "` or regular expression `/\s{1}/`).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] When a token class represents more than one possible lexeme, the lexer often saves enough information to reproduce the original lexeme, so that it can be used in semantic analysis.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The parser typically retrieves this information from the lexer and stores it in the abstract syntax tree.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This is necessary in order to avoid information loss in the case where numbers may also be valid identifiers.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Tokens are identified based on the specific rules of the lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Some methods used to identify tokens include regular expressions, specific sequences of characters termed a flag, specific separating characters called delimiters, and explicit definition by a dictionary.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Special characters, including punctuation characters, are commonly used by lexers to identify tokens because of their natural use in written and programming languages.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A lexical analyzer generally does nothing with combinations of tokens, a task left for a parser.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] For example, a typical lexical analyzer recognizes parentheses as tokens but does nothing to ensure that each "(" is matched with a ")".
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] When a lexer feeds tokens to the parser, the representation used is typically an enumerated type, which is a list of number representations.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] For example, "Identifier" can be represented with 0, "Assignment operator" with 1, "Addition operator" with 2, etc.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Tokens are often defined by regular expressions, which are understood by a lexical analyzer generator such as lex, or handcoded equivalent finite-state automata.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The lexical analyzer (generated automatically by a tool like lex or hand-crafted) reads in a stream of characters, identifies the lexemes in the stream, and categorizes them into tokens.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] If the lexer finds an invalid token, it will report an error.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] From there, the interpreted data may be loaded into data structures for general use, interpretation, or compiling.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The specification of a programming language often includes a set of rules, the lexical grammar, which defines the lexical syntax.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The lexical syntax is usually a regular language, with the grammar rules consisting of regular expressions; they define the set of possible character sequences (lexemes) of a token.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A lexer recognizes strings, and for each kind of string found, the lexical program takes an action, most simply producing a token.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Two important common lexical categories are white space and comments.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These are also defined in the grammar and processed by the lexer but may be discarded (not producing any tokens) and considered *non-significant*, at most separating two tokens (as in `if x` instead of `ifx`).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] There are two important exceptions to this.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] First, in off-side rule languages that delimit blocks with indenting, initial whitespace is significant, as it determines block structure, and is generally handled at the lexer level; see phrase structure, below.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Secondly, in some uses of lexers, comments and whitespace must be preserved – for examples, a prettyprinter also needs to output the comments and some debugging tools may provide messages to the programmer showing the original source code.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] In the 1960s, notably for ALGOL, whitespace and comments were eliminated as part of the line reconstruction phase (the initial phase of the compiler frontend), but this separate phase has been eliminated and these are now handled by the lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The first stage, the *scanner*, is usually based on a finite-state machine (FSM).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] It has encoded within it information on the possible sequences of characters that can be contained within any of the tokens it handles (individual instances of these character sequences are termed lexemes).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] For example, an *integer* lexeme may contain any sequence of numerical digit characters.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] In some languages, the lexeme creation rules are more complex and may involve backtracking over previously read characters.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] For example, in C, one 'L' character is not enough to distinguish between an identifier that begins with 'L' and a wide-character string literal.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A lexeme, however, is only a string of characters known to be of a certain kind (e.g., a string literal, a sequence of letters).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The second stage of a lexical analyzer, the *evaluator*, goes over the characters of the lexeme to produce a *value* containing relevant information for the parser.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The lexeme's type combined with its value is what properly constitutes a *token*.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The value in the token can be whatever is deemed necessary for the parser to interpret a token of that type.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The evaluator may also suppress a lexeme entirely, concealing it from the parser, which is useful for whitespace and comments.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This is practical if the list of tokens is small, but lexers generated by automated tooling as part of a compiler-compiler toolchain are more practical for a larger number of potential tokens.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These tools generally accept regular expressions that describe the tokens allowed in the input stream.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Each regular expression is associated with a production rule in the lexical grammar of the programming language that evaluates the lexemes matching the regular expression.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These tools may generate source code that can be compiled and executed or construct a state transition table for a finite-state machine (which is plugged into template code for compiling and executing).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Regular expressions compactly represent patterns that the characters in lexemes might follow.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] For example, for an English-based language, an IDENTIFIER token might be any English alphabetic character or an underscore, followed by any number of instances of ASCII alphanumeric characters and/or underscores.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This could be represented compactly by the string `[a-zA-Z_][a-zA-Z_0-9]*`.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This means "any character a-z, A-Z or _, followed by 0 or more of a-z, A-Z, _ or 0-9".
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] It takes a full parser to recognize such patterns in their full generality.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A parser can push parentheses on a stack and then try to pop them off and see if the stack is empty at the end (see example in the *Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs* book).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Typically, lexical tokenization occurs at the word level.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] However, it is sometimes difficult to define what is meant by a "word".
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] In languages that use inter-word spaces (such as most that use the Latin alphabet, and most programming languages), this approach is fairly straightforward.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] However, even here there are many edge cases such as contractions, hyphenated words, emoticons, and larger constructs such as URIs (which for some purposes may count as single tokens).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A classic example is "New York-based", which a naive tokenizer may break at the space even though the better break is (arguably) at the hyphen.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Tokenization is particularly difficult for languages written in scriptio continua, which exhibit no word boundaries, such as Ancient Greek, Chinese, or Thai.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Agglutinative languages, such as Korean, also make tokenization tasks complicated.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Some ways to address the more difficult problems include developing more complex heuristics, querying a table of common special cases, or fitting the tokens to a language model that identifies collocations in a later processing step.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexers are often generated by a *lexer generator*, analogous to parser generators, and such tools often come together.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The most established is lex, paired with the yacc parser generator, or rather some of their many reimplementations, like flex (often paired with GNU Bison).
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These generators are a form of domain-specific language, taking in a lexical specification – generally regular expressions with some markup – and emitting a lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These tools yield very fast development, which is very important in early development, both to get a working lexer and because a language specification may change often.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Further, they often provide advanced features, such as pre- and post-conditions which are hard to program by hand.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] However, an automatically generated lexer may lack flexibility, and thus may require some manual modification, or an all-manually written lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexer performance is a concern, and optimizing is worthwhile, more so in stable languages where the lexer runs very often (such as C or HTML). lex/flex-generated lexers are reasonably fast, but improvements of two to three times are possible using more tuned generators.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Hand-written lexers are sometimes used, but modern lexer generators produce faster lexers than most hand-coded ones.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The lex/flex family of generators uses a table-driven approach which is much less efficient than the directly coded approach.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] With the latter approach the generator produces an engine that directly jumps to follow-up states via goto statements.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Tools like re2c have proven to produce engines that are between two and three times faster than flex produced engines.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] It is in general difficult to hand-write analyzers that perform better than engines generated by these latter tools.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Lexical analysis mainly segments the input stream of characters into tokens, simply grouping the characters into pieces and categorizing them.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] However, the lexing may be significantly more complex; most simply, lexers may omit tokens or insert added tokens.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Omitting tokens, notably whitespace and comments, is very common when these are not needed by the compiler.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Less commonly, added tokens may be inserted.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This is done mainly to group tokens into statements, or statements into blocks, to simplify the parser.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Line continuation is a feature of some languages where a newline is normally a statement terminator.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Most often, ending a line with a backslash (immediately followed by a newline) results in the line being *continued* – the following line is *joined* to the prior line.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This is generally done in the lexer: The backslash and newline are discarded, rather than the newline being tokenized.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Examples include bash, other shell scripts and Python.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Many languages use the semicolon as a statement terminator.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Most often this is mandatory, but in some languages the semicolon is optional in many contexts.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This is mainly done at the lexer level, where the lexer outputs a semicolon into the token stream, despite one not being present in the input character stream, and is termed *semicolon insertion* or *automatic semicolon insertion*.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] In these cases, semicolons are part of the formal phrase grammar of the language, but may not be found in input text, as they can be inserted by the lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Optional semicolons or other terminators or separators are also sometimes handled at the parser level, notably in the case of trailing commas or semicolons.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is a feature of BCPL and its distant descendant Go, though it is absent in B or C.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Semicolon insertion is present in JavaScript, though the rules are somewhat complex and much-criticized; to avoid bugs, some recommend always using semicolons, while others use initial semicolons, termed defensive semicolons, at the start of potentially ambiguous statements.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] The off-side rule (blocks determined by indenting) can be implemented in the lexer, as in Python, where increasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting an INDENT token and decreasing the indenting results in the lexer emitting one or more DEDENT tokens.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These tokens correspond to the opening brace `{` and closing brace `}` in languages that use braces for blocks and means that the phrase grammar does not depend on whether braces or indenting are used.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This requires that the lexer hold state, namely a stack of indent levels, and thus can detect changes in indenting when this changes, and thus the lexical grammar is not context-free: INDENT–DEDENT depend on the contextual information of prior indent levels.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Generally lexical grammars are context-free, or almost so, and thus require no looking back or ahead, or backtracking, which allows a simple, clean, and efficient implementation.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] This also allows simple one-way communication from lexer to parser, without needing any information flowing back to the lexer.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] These examples all only require lexical context, and while they complicate a lexer somewhat, they are invisible to the parser and later phases.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] A more complex example is the lexer hack in C, where the token class of a sequence of characters cannot be determined until the semantic analysis phase since typedef names and variable names are lexically identical but constitute different token classes.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] Thus in the hack, the lexer calls the semantic analyzer (say, symbol table) and checks if the sequence requires a typedef name.
[src:lex-yacc/lexical-analysis] In this case, information must flow back not from the parser only, but from the semantic analyzer back to the lexer, which complicates design.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Johnson, a computer scientist at Bell Labs / AT&T, developed Yacc because he wanted to insert an exclusive or operator into a B language compiler (developed using McIlroy's TMG compiler-compiler), but it turned out to be a hard task.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] As a result, he was directed by his colleague at Bell Labs Al Aho to Donald Knuth's work on LR parsing, which served as the basis for Yacc.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc was influenced by and received its name in reference to TMG compiler-compiler.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc was originally written in the B programming language, but was soon rewritten in C by Alan Snyder.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] It appeared as part of Version 3 Unix, and a full description of Yacc was published in 1975.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Johnson used Yacc to create the Portable C Compiler.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Bjarne Stroustrup also attempted to use Yacc to create a formal specification of C++, but "was defeated by C's syntax".
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] While finding it unsuitable for a formal specification of the language, Stroustrup did proceed to use Yacc to implement Cfront, the first implementation of C++.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] In a 2008 interview, Johnson reflected that "the contribution Yacc made to the spread of Unix and C is what I'm proudest of".
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] The input to Yacc is a grammar with snippets of C code (called "actions") attached to its rules.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Its output is a shift-reduce parser in C that executes the C snippets associated with each rule as soon as the rule is recognized.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Typical actions involve the construction of parse trees.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] recognizes summation expressions and constructs nodes for them.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] The special identifiers $$, $1 and $3 refer to items on the parser's stack.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc produces only a parser (phrase analyzer) which can be used alone in the case of scannerless parsing however, full syntactic analysis typically requires an external lexical analyzer to perform a tokenization stage first (word analysis), which is then followed by the parsing stage proper.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Lexical analyzer generators, such as Lex or Flex, are widely available for this purpose.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] The IEEE POSIX P1003.2 standard defines the functionality and requirements for both Lex and Yacc.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Some versions of AT&T Yacc have become open source.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] For example, source code is available with the standard distributions of Plan 9.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc and similar programs (largely reimplementations) have been very popular.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc itself used to be available as the default parser generator on most Unix systems, though it has since been supplanted by more recent, largely compatible, programs such as Berkeley Yacc, GNU Bison, MKS Yacc, and Abraxas PCYACC.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] An updated version of the original AT&T Yacc is included as part of Sun's OpenSolaris project.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Each offers slight improvements and additional features over the original Yacc, but the concept and basic syntax have remained the same.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc was also one of several UNIX tools available for Charles River Data Systems' UNOS operating system under Bell Laboratories license.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Among the languages that were first implemented with Yacc are AWK, C++, eqn and Pic.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc was also used on Unix to implement the Portable C Compiler, as well as parsers for such programming languages as FORTRAN 77, Ratfor, APL, bc, m4, etc.
[src:lex-yacc/yacc] Yacc has also been rewritten for other languages, including OCaml, Ratfor, ML, Ada, Pascal, Java, PHP, Python, Ruby, Go, Common Lisp and Erlang.
